data.body:
I am trying to convert over an XNA project to MonoGame and run into an issue with passing Textures into a custom shader.  Essentially the shader parameter to pass the Texture2D object in on the C# side doesn't exist.  (I'll post the shader at the end)

``` C#
SomeEffect.Parameters["SomeTexture"] //Is null because the parameter doesn't exist in the object.
```

I'm assuming (which could be a horrible idea) that the way you pass Texture2D objects into shaders for Monogame is the same as XNA.

I swapped out the dll contained with the installer with the source from develop for MonoGameContentProcessors and flipped the debugger on during a build to see what was up.

It never hits the code that would build the sampler into the Effect object.
[ShaderData.sharpdx.cs Line: 54](https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/blob/develop/Tools/2MGFX/ShaderData.sharpdx.cs#L54)

``` C#
if (rdesc.Type == SharpDX.D3DCompiler.ShaderInputType.Texture)
```

 During the PS pass for CreateHLSL there are no bound resources and for the VS there is one with a Type of "ConstantBuffer" When the constant buffer is later parsed it does correctly contain the 3 global parameters that the shader has.

I am unsure if there is a bug in SharpDX's D3DCompiler that generates the bytecode, something in the parser of the reflected object, or my environment/config/etc.  Maybe it's a combination of each.

```
float4x4 View;
float4x4 Projection;

int Time;

Texture2D PhotoTexture : register (t0);
sampler PhotoSampler : register (s0);

struct VertexShaderInput
{
    float4 Position : SV_Position;
    float3 Normal   : NORMAL0;
    float2 UV : TEXCOORD0;

};

struct VertexShaderOutput
{
    float4 Position : SV_Position;
    float3 Normal   : NORMAL0;
    float2 UV : TEXCOORD0;

};

VertexShaderOutput VertexShaderFunction(VertexShaderInput Input)
{

    VertexShaderOutput Output;

    Output.Position = mul(Input.Position, mul(View, Projection));
    Output.Normal = Input.Normal;
    Output.UV = Input.UV;

    return Output;

}

float4 PixelShaderFunction(VertexShaderOutput input) : SV_Target
{

    float4 Color = PhotoTexture.Sample(PhotoSampler, input.UV);

    float Alpha = clamp((Time - input.Normal.x) * input.Normal.y / 255, 0, 1);

    return float4(0.5, 0.5, 1, 1);

}

technique Technique1
{

    pass Pass1
    {

        VertexShader = compile vs_5_0 VertexShaderFunction();
        PixelShader = compile ps_5_0 PixelShaderFunction();

    }

}
```

My environment is...

Windows 8.1 x64
VS2013 Ultimate Update 1
MonoGamePlatform is set to "Windows8" (I've confirmed this is being passed into the pipeline correctly with the debugger)
Additional info as needed.

The [following lines](https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/blob/develop/MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/GraphicsDevice.OpenGL.cs#L299) cause an InvalidFramebufferOperation when isRenderbufferTargetBound is true:

``` csharp
        private void PlatformSetViewport(ref Viewport value)
        {
            if (IsRenderTargetBound)
                GL.Viewport(value.X, value.Y, value.Width, value.Height);
            else
                GL.Viewport(value.X, PresentationParameters.BackBufferHeight - value.Y - value.Height, value.Width, value.Height);
            GraphicsExtensions.LogGLError("GraphicsDevice.Viewport_set() GL.Viewport");
```

This appears to occur even if the renderbuffer and the viewport have the same size. I can only reproduce on the Mac backend, not WindowsGL or Linux.

Tested on Mac SOS 10.9.2 with an Nvidia 650M.
